Ordered online for pickup. The Smoky Blue bison burger was cooked to medium as requested.  The burger was juicy and tasted great. The onion rings were decent, I thought the breading was little salty and not as good as a beer battered onion ring.  I think they should make their various sauces available at no charge to the customers.  I think people would really like trying some of the sauces, but I'm sure they are reluctant due to the small upcharge. If you have that craving for a filling, juicy burger, Bareburger will scratch that itch, but at a higher price than other burger restaurants.  The online ordering process was fairly simple. FYI- they don't text your phone when the order is ready, they send an email.

He said, they were all there & that it was just tighter.  Then the wrap would be bigger in circumference, right? We really want to love it here and every few months give it another try as the location is convenient and food is decent.  Unfortunately we always leave feeling frustrated. On our most recent visit we waited 15-20 minutes for our burgers, it wasn’t very busy, but ok fine. However I ordered the impossible burger off the menu, and was disappointed when I received a patty in a bun with no toppings. Mistakes happen, I asked if they would mind adding the toppings. They came back a few minutes later, had placed the same patty in a new bun and had added a piece of lettuce. When I realized this was all they had added, I asked again if they could please add the rest of the toppings.  They went away, came back a few minutes later to explain they were out of caramelized onions and so didn’t put the toppings on. I stated that’s fine but it would have been nice to have been told when I ordered...or even the first time I sent the burger back...as I paid for the burger as described and would have happily just built my own burger rather than paying more money for essentially a patty on a bun.  They apologised that it was expensive and explained that normally the kitchen explain to the front when they are out of an item but it’s a new team so they didn’t tell anyone...I realized I was getting nowhere so let it go.  They did offer me fries and milkshake, but I’d already paid for my own sweet fries and ordering vegan burger wasn’t that interested in milkshake...Annoyingly a few minutes later, no joke, 4 or 5 impossible burgers came out of the kitchen to the tables near us and they all had toppings.  In the grand scheme of things, not that important, but there are plenty of other locations and restaurants with less hassle where you might get what you paid for! We paid $47 for two burgers as they come and a shared portion of sweet fries, and got less than we paid for.  As it was one of several bad experiences with same location, thought it was time to share.

In Manhattan a world everything based on Money. I felt glad to know this restaurant.  So I checked quite a lots got the information about this chained burgers store. here are what I found from other's articles  "If you are in New York City and looking for a casual, paleo-friendly meal you should check out Bareburger."  "BareBurger’s atmosphere is rough-hewn, utilizing reclaimed materials, sustainable bamboo floors, cork walls and high tech hand dryers in the bathrooms. The service is friendly and casual, making all the BareBurger locations ideal for families, friends and casual dates. Debra, an executive from the organization, visits all locations and helps to ensure quality and consistency. A farm girl herself, she says this is one of the nicest places to work thanks to the lovely staff. You can taste the good karma in the food.  The walls are adorned with peculiar portraits of animal heads featured on human bodies, a part of their signature decor.  The tables continue to demonstrate the theme as they are cut from tree trunk, offering a more whimsical place to eat."  "Aside from the unique decor, the wide array of meats stood out on the Bareburger menu.  The burgers contain anything from beef and chicken to wild boar and elk. They are served on either a sprout bun or brioche bun, and topped with various greens, cheeses, and sauces. Patrons can either choose from the signature burgers or build their own. Bareburger offers several “All-American” appetizers to start off the meal. To accommodate our party of five we chose the Macho Fries, fries topped with guacamole, cheese, jalapeños, and buttermilk ranch.After the Macho Fries, trying an adventurous route and chose the Elk Burger comprised of an elk patty and blue cheese. Served in a rustic metal tray lined with layers of tissue paper, the unusual combination of country bacon, onions, tomato, and fig jam blended together perfectly. However, this burger does require an acquired taste for the blue cheese. In addition, this is not the choice for those looking to eat healthy—this burger, unlike most of the others, actually does not have any greens. We also decided to build our own burger. Desiring something specifically fit for our taste, we decided to choose the duck patty in a brioche bun, spilling over with cheese. We also chose crispy lettuce and sweet marinated sauce. Yet, these are not the only toppings one can choose for his/her burger. The ‘Be My Burger’ option provides a variety of patties, buns, cheeses, veggies, sauces, and spreads that can be used to build your burger. Not only does it give you a backup in case you don’t like any of the signature burgers, but it also gives you the freedom to try new things.  Although the food here is a bit on the pricey side, the staff made up for it with exceptional service and courteous waiters that accommodated the customers’ needs. Even during shift changes, the process was smooth and did not interrupt our meal in any way. Bareburger also has other sandwiches, drinks, and desserts to choose from if you are not a fan of burgers." Thanks for all above sentence and words. let me know about this burger restaurant. -----and I would like to share with others. Hopefully this will be useful
